REV_ORIGINAL = {
  "1": {
    "1": "<p><strong>apokalypsis Iesou Christou</strong>: 'Revelation/disclosure of Jesus Christ.' <em>Apokalypsis</em> (G0602) names the genre: an unveiling of what is hidden. The genitive is double: Jesus Christ is both the source (revelation given by/through him) and the content (revelation about him). <em>Dei genesthai en tachei</em> — must happen soon: <em>dei</em> (divine necessity, the language of God's sovereign plan) + <em>en tachei</em> (in swiftness/soon; not 'soon' in the sense of within a calendar, but with urgency — the apocalyptic 'soon' of imminence). <em>Esēmanen</em> (signified/made known by signs): from <em>sēmeion</em> (sign/symbol), implying the book communicates through symbolic-visionary language, not straightforward prediction.</p>",
    "2": "<p><strong>emartyresin ton logon tou theou kai tēn martyrian Iesou Christou</strong>: 'bore witness to the word of God and to the testimony of Jesus Christ.' <em>Emartyresin</em> (aorist): John's witness is a completed act — he recorded everything he saw. The double genitive <em>martyria Iesou</em> is programmatic: it means both the testimony about Jesus (objective genitive) and the testimony belonging to Jesus/which Jesus himself gives (subjective genitive); the ambiguity is deliberate throughout Revelation.</p>",
    "3": "<p><strong>makarios ho anaginōskōn kai hoi akouontes</strong>: 'Blessed is the one who reads aloud, and blessed are those who hear.' The singular <em>anaginōskōn</em> (one reading aloud) and plural <em>akouontes</em> (those hearing) reflect early Christian practice: one lector reading the scroll in the assembly, many listeners — the book was composed to be performed. <em>Terountes ta en autē gegrammena</em>: keeping/obeying (present participle, ongoing) what is written — hearing alone is not the blessing; the blessing belongs to those who hear and keep.</p>",
    "4": "<p><strong>ho ōn kai ho ēn kai ho erchomenos</strong>: 'the one who is and who was and who is to come.' The phrase is syntactically remarkable: instead of <em>ho esomenos</em> (who will be), John writes <em>ho erchomenos</em> (who is coming). God is not merely 'the one who will exist' but 'the one who is coming' — his futurity is active arrival, not passive existence. The seven spirits before the throne (v. 4) alludes to Isa 11:2's sevenfold Spirit; the number seven = completeness/perfection, so this is the fullness of the Holy Spirit's presence.</p>",
    "5": "<p><strong>ho martys ho pistos, ho prōtotokos tōn nekrōn, ho archōn tōn basileōn tēs gēs</strong>: three titles in a single phrase. <em>Martys</em> (witness): in Revelation, 'witness' carries the weight of one who testifies at cost of life — Jesus is the faithful witness because his testimony led to his death (the semantic development toward 'martyr'). <em>Prōtotokos tōn nekrōn</em> (firstborn of the dead): not born first among the dead but the one who inaugurates resurrection — the 'firstborn' as the one who opens the womb of death (Col 1:18 parallel). <em>Ho agapōnti hēmas</em>: present participle — not 'who loved us' (past) but 'the one who loves us' (ongoing present love).</p>",
    "6": "<p><strong>epoiēsen hēmas basileian hiereis</strong>: 'made us a kingdom, priests.' The aorist <em>epoiēsen</em> marks this as accomplished fact, not future aspiration. The construction alludes to Exod 19:6 LXX (<em>basileion hierateuma</em>, royal priesthood) — what Israel was called to be at Sinai has been constituted in Christ. The MKT follows the reading <em>basileian hiereis</em> (a kingdom, priests) rather than <em>basileion hierateuma</em> (royal priesthood), following Codex Alexandrinus; the meaning is the same: priestly mediation joined to royal authority.</p>",
    "7": "<p><strong>idou erchetai meta tōn nephelōn</strong>: present tense coming — not 'will come' (<em>eleusetai</em>) but 'is coming' (<em>erchetai</em>), the same present used of Christ's coming throughout Revelation; the parousia is in motion. <em>Kopsetai ep auton pasai hai phylai tēs gēs</em>: 'all the tribes of the earth will mourn/wail for him' — <em>kopsomai</em> is the word for funeral lamentation; Zech 12:10-12 uses it for the mourning over the pierced one. <em>Nai kai amēn</em>: double affirmation, combining Greek (<em>nai</em>) and Hebrew/Aramaic (<em>amēn</em>) for emphatic certainty.</p>",
    "8": "<p><strong>ego eimi to Alpha kai to Omega legei Kyrios ho Theos ho on kai ho en kai ho erchomenos ho Pantokrator</strong>: 'I am the Alpha and the Omega, says the Lord God, who is and who was and who is to come, the Almighty.' <em>Alpha kai Omega</em>: the first and last letters of the Greek alphabet — a comprehensive inclusio encompassing all of reality. The phrase is applied both to God the Father (1:8; 21:6) and to Jesus (22:13: 'I am the Alpha and the Omega, the first and the last, the beginning and the end') — the shared title making the Christological identification with YHWH explicit. <em>Pantokrator</em> (Almighty): the LXX translation of Hebrew <em>El Shaddai</em> and <em>YHWH Tsvaot</em> (LORD of hosts) — here applied to both Father and Son as the supreme governing power over all creation.</p>",
    "9": "<p><strong>synkoinōnos en tē thlipsei kai basileia kai hypomonē</strong>: 'fellow-partaker in the affliction and kingdom and patient endurance.' The three nouns are linked by a single article (<em>tē</em>): affliction, kingdom, and endurance are a single package — the kingdom is already present, but the path through it requires endurance of affliction. <em>Hypomonē</em> (patient endurance) is not passive waiting but active staying under pressure. John is in <em>thlipsis</em> (affliction) on Patmos because of witness — not despite his relationship to the kingdom but as the form that kingdom-life takes under opposition.</p>",
    "10": "<p><strong>egenomēn en pneumati en tē kyriakē hēmera</strong>: 'I came to be in the Spirit on the Lord's day.' <em>Egenomēn</em> (aorist): a moment of transition — John entered a state of Spirit-possession. <em>Kyriakē hēmera</em> (Lord's Day) is the first occurrence of this phrase in the NT; it identifies Sunday as the day of Christian assembly in commemoration of the resurrection. <em>Phōnēn opisthen mou hōs salpiggos</em>: voice behind him like a trumpet — the spatial disorientation (behind, not in front) and the trumpet sound signal divine address; compare Exod 19:16 (trumpet sound at Sinai).</p>",
    "11": "<p><strong>ho blepeis grapson eis biblion kai pempson tais hepta ekklēsiais</strong>: 'What you see, write into a scroll and send to the seven churches.' The commission is visual-to-written: John is commanded to transcribe his vision (<em>ho blepeis</em>, what you are seeing) as a letter to seven named communities. The seven churches are historically identifiable cities in Roman Asia (modern western Turkey) along a roughly circular mail route — the Revelation was a circular letter intended to be read in each assembly.</p>",
    "12": "<p><strong>hepta lychnias chrysas</strong>: seven golden lampstands. The lampstand (<em>lychnia</em>) is the menorah-form of the tabernacle and temple (Exod 25:31-40), redeployed here for seven separate churches. Christ walking <em>en mesō tōn hepta lychniōn</em> (in the midst of the seven lampstands) recalls the priestly role of tending the menorah — Christ as the heavenly priest maintaining/attending to the churches, his seven-fold presence among them.</p>",
    "13": "<p><strong>homoion huion anthrōpou</strong>: 'like a son of man' — <em>homoion</em> + accusative, not the full Danielic title but the allusive vision-form (Dan 7:13; 10:16). The description that follows combines Daniel's heavenly figure with Ezekiel's: <em>endedymenon podērē</em> (clothed to the feet: the priestly/royal long robe), <em>periezōsmenon pros tois mastois zonēn chrysēn</em> (girded at the chest with a golden sash — the position of the sash shifts from the waist, where soldiers wear it, to the chest, the position of seated authority or priestly service).</p>",
    "14": "<p><strong>hē kephalē autou kai hai triches leukai hōs erion leukon hōs chiōn</strong>: head and hair white as wool, white as snow — drawn directly from the Ancient of Days in Dan 7:9 (the divine throne-figure with white like wool). By applying this description to the glorified Christ, Revelation identifies Jesus with the divine throne-figure of Daniel. <em>Hoi ophthalmoi autou hōs phlox pyros</em> (eyes like a flame of fire): from Dan 10:6, the heavenly man with eyes like torches of fire — omniscience and penetrating judgment.</p>",
    "15": "<p><strong>hoi podes autou homoioi chalkolibanō hōs en kaminos pepyrōmenēs</strong>: feet like burnished bronze/electrum, as if refined in a furnace — from Dan 10:6 and Ezek 1:7 (gleaming bronze). <em>Chalkolibanos</em> is a hapax legomenon in the NT, possibly meaning a precious brass alloy or incense-copper; its exact identification is uncertain, but the refined-in-fire imagery signals purification and solidity. <em>Kai hē phōnē autou hōs phōnē hydatōn pollōn</em>: voice like many waters — Ezek 43:2's description of God's voice returning to the restored temple.</p>",
    "16": "<p><strong>echōn en tē dexia cheiri autou asteras hepta kai ek tou stomatos autou rhomphaia distomos oxeia ekporeuomenē</strong>: holding seven stars in his right hand; from his mouth a sharp double-edged sword. <em>Rhomphaia</em> (the large Thracian sword, a broad-bladed weapon) rather than <em>machaira</em> (the short sword) — Revelation consistently uses <em>rhomphaia</em> for the sword from Christ's mouth (1:16; 2:12, 16; 19:15, 21), perhaps to emphasize its imposing, judicial weight. The sword from the mouth = the word of divine judgment: Christ's weapon is speech, not physical force.</p>",
    "17": "<p><strong>ego eimi ho protos kai ho eschatos kai ho zon kai egenomen nekros kai idou zon eimi eis tous aionas ton aionon</strong>: 'I am the first and the last, and the living one. I died, and behold I am alive forevermore.' The phrase <em>ho protos kai ho eschatos</em> (first and last) is YHWH's self-identification in Isa 41:4; 44:6; 48:12 — the exclusive divine claim to be both origin and terminus of all history. Jesus applies this YHWH-title to himself in combination with the resurrection claim: 'I died and behold I am alive.' The resurrection is the proof that the crucified one is the living YHWH — the divine identity claim vindicated by rising from death.</p>",
    "18": "<p><strong>echō tas kleidas tou thanatou kai tou Hadou</strong>: 'I hold the keys of Death and Hades.' <em>Echō</em> (present tense): Christ currently and continuously possesses these keys — this is his present status as the risen one. Death and Hades are personified as a paired power throughout Revelation (6:8; 20:13-14), functioning as the last enemies; to hold their keys is to control entry and exit from the realm of the dead. The resurrection is not just Christ's personal survival but his seizure of authority over the entire structure of mortality.</p>",
    "19": "<p><strong>grapson oun ha eideskon kai ha eisin kai ha mellei genesthai meta tauta</strong>: 'Write therefore what you saw and what is and what is to take place after this.' The three-part formula has generated debate about Revelation's structure: (1) what you saw = ch. 1 vision; (2) what is = chs. 2-3 (the churches as they presently are); (3) what is to come = chs. 4-22. <em>Ha mellei genesthai</em>: the events that are about to happen — <em>mellei</em> (is about to) again signals imminence.</p>",
    "20": "<p><strong>to mystērion tōn hepta asterōn... kai tas hepta lychnias tas chrysas</strong>: 'the mystery of the seven stars... and the seven golden lampstands.' <em>Mystērion</em> (mystery): a secret that has been disclosed — the vision's imagery is explained by Christ himself. The seven stars are <em>angeloi</em> (messengers/angels) of the seven churches — whether guardian angels, heavenly representatives, or human leaders (bishops/overseers) is debated; the usage allows both. The lampstands are the churches themselves, visible light-bearers in the world, tended by the one who walks among them.</p>"
  },
  "2": {
    "1": "<p><strong>tō angelō tēs en Ephesō ekklēsias grapson</strong>: 'To the messenger of the church in Ephesus write.' Each letter is addressed to the <em>angelos</em> (messenger/angel) of the church — this figure is either the church's guardian angel or, more likely given the context of human accountability, the leader/bishop who embodies and represents the community. <em>Kratōn tous hepta asteras</em> (holding the seven stars): <em>kratōn</em> is present participle — ongoing, continuous possession and governance. <em>Peripatōn en mesō</em>: walking among (present participle) — active, continuous pastoral presence.</p>",
    "2": "<p><strong>oida ta erga sou kai ton kopon kai tēn hypomonēn sou</strong>: 'I know your deeds, your labor, and your patient endurance.' <em>Oida</em> (perfect, used as present): I have come to know and know now — Christ's knowledge is comprehensive and current. <em>Kopos</em> (labor) is more intense than general <em>ergon</em> (work): it implies toiling effort, wearying exertion. <em>Ou dynē bastasai kakous</em>: you are not able to tolerate evil people — <em>bastasai</em> (bear, carry) suggests they have tested false teachers and found them wanting, bearing the weight of that discernment.</p>",
    "3": "<p><strong>kai hypomonēn echeis kai ebastasas dia to onoma mou kai ou kekopiakas</strong>: 'You have endurance and you have borne burdens for my name and have not grown weary.' The aorist <em>ebastasas</em> (you have borne/carried) describes completed past endurance; <em>ou kekopiakas</em> (you have not grown weary) is perfect — the state of not-having-wearied persists. The Ephesian church's endurance record is strong; the contrast with v. 4 is deliberate.</p>",
    "4": "<p><strong>alla echō kata sou hoti tēn agapēn sou tēn prōtēn aphēkes</strong>: 'But I have this against you: you have abandoned your first love.' <em>Aphēkes</em> (aorist): you let go, you released, you abandoned — a deliberate action, not gradual drift. <em>Tēn agapēn sou tēn prōtēn</em>: the first/original love (prōtēn = first in time, prior love). The Ephesians' doctrinal vigilance (vv. 2-3) has come at the cost of the relational vitality that animated their original faith.</p>",
    "5": "<p><strong>mnēmoneue pothen peptōkas kai metanoēson kai ta prōta erga poiēson</strong>: 'Remember from where you have fallen; repent; and do the first works.' Three aorist imperatives in sequence — remember, repent, do — forming a program of restoration. <em>Peptōkas</em> (perfect): you have fallen and remain in the fallen state. <em>Kinēsō tēn lychnian sou ek tou topou autēs</em>: I will move/remove your lampstand from its place — removal is the consequence of non-repentance; the church ceases to function as a light-bearer.</p>",
    "6": "<p><strong>alla touto echeis hoti miseis ta erga tōn Nikolaitōn ha kagō misō</strong>: 'But you have this: you hate the practices of the Nicolaitans, which I also hate.' <em>Miseis</em> and <em>misō</em> (present tense) — strong active hatred, the same verb applied to both the church and to Christ; the community's revulsion at the Nicolaitan practice is validated by Christ's own attitude. The Nicolaitans are associated with the Balaam-teaching (v. 14-15): eating food sacrificed to idols and sexual immorality, possibly an antinomian group that accommodated to Greco-Roman social norms.</p>",
    "7": "<p><strong>tō nikōnti dōsō autō phagein ek tou xylou tēs zōēs</strong>: 'To the one who overcomes I will give to eat from the tree of life.' <em>Nikōnti</em> (present participle, dative): to the one who is conquering — ongoing victory, not a single past act. The closing formula <em>ho echōn ous akousatō ti to pneuma legei tais ekklēsiais</em> appears at the end of each letter: the Spirit's address to one church is for all seven churches — the letter is simultaneously specific and universal.</p>",
    "8": "<p><strong>ho prōtos kai ho eschatos, hos egeneto nekros kai ezēsen</strong>: 'the First and the Last, who died and came to life.' The YHWH-title from Isa 44:6 (first and last) is linked to the resurrection fact: the one who claims the divine identity-marker is the one who died and rose. <em>Egeneto nekros kai ezēsen</em>: became dead and lived — both aorists, two completed historical events. To the Smyrna church facing poverty and potential death, Christ presents his own death-and-life as the paradigm for what they face.</p>",
    "9": "<p><strong>oida sou tēn thlipsin kai tēn ptōcheian, alla plousios ei</strong>: 'I know your affliction and your poverty — yet you are rich.' The contrast is direct: material poverty (<em>ptōcheia</em>, utter destitution) against spiritual wealth. <em>Blasphēmian tōn legontōn Ioudaious einai heautous kai ouk eisin alla synagōgē tou satana</em>: the slander from those claiming to be Jews but not being so. The phrase <em>synagōgē tou satana</em> (synagogue of Satan) is polemical: those who claim the covenant name but oppose the Messiah have become, functionally, the assembly of the adversary rather than the assembly of God.</p>",
    "10": "<p><strong>mēden phobou ha melleis paschein</strong>: 'Fear nothing of what you are about to suffer.' <em>Melleis paschein</em> (about to suffer): imminent, foreseeable suffering. <em>Deka hēmeras</em> (ten days): a limited, defined period — alluding to the ten-day testing of Daniel and his companions (Dan 1:12-15); the number signals that the trial, however severe, is bounded by God's will. <em>Stephanos tēs zōēs</em> (crown of life): <em>stephanos</em> is the victor's laurel wreath, not the royal diadem (<em>diadēma</em>) — the image is athletic/competitive: those who compete faithfully receive the life-wreath.</p>",
    "11": "<p><strong>ho nikōn ou mē adikēthē ek tou deuterou thanatou</strong>: 'The one who overcomes will not be harmed by the second death.' The double negative <em>ou mē</em> with subjunctive is the strongest Greek negation — absolute certainty of exemption. <em>Ho deuteros thanatos</em> (the second death) is Revelation's term for permanent separation from God after final judgment (20:6, 14; 21:8) — the lake of fire. The promise to faithful Smyrna: physical death cannot touch them where it ultimately matters.</p>",
    "12": "<p><strong>ho echōn tēn rhomphian tēn distomon tēn oxeian</strong>: 'the one who has the sharp double-edged sword.' The self-identification of Christ to Pergamum uses the sword-from-mouth imagery of 1:16 — relevant because Pergamum was the capital of Roman Asia and the seat of Roman judicial authority; Christ presents himself as the ultimate judge whose word supersedes Rome's verdict. The Roman proconsul exercised <em>ius gladii</em> (right of the sword) — the power of execution. Christ's sword-of-the-mouth counters this claim.</p>",
    "13": "<p><strong>ho thronos tou satana</strong>: 'the throne of Satan' — Pergamum was the location of the imperial cult in Asia, with a major altar to Augustus/Rome, and the great altar of Zeus (possibly the altar now reconstructed in Berlin). <em>Antipas ho martys mou ho pistos</em>: Antipas my faithful witness — the use of <em>martys</em> (witness) for one who died for the faith marks the semantic evolution toward 'martyr.' <em>Ho katechoumenoi tēn didachēn Balaam</em>: those holding to the teaching of Balaam — a syncretistic accommodation to imperial cult practices.</p>",
    "14": "<p><strong>tēn didachēn Balaam, hos edidasken ton Balak balein skandalon enōpion tōn huiōn Israēl, phagein eidōlothyta kai porneusai</strong>: 'the teaching of Balaam, who taught Balak to put a stumbling block before the children of Israel, so that they might eat food sacrificed to idols and practice sexual immorality.' <em>Skandalon</em> (stumbling block/snare): the metaphor of a trap. <em>Eidōlothyta</em> (idol-food): food offered in sacrifice to Greco-Roman deities — eating it at temple banquets was socially expected in trade guilds; the refusal to eat separated Christians from normal social life. <em>Porneusai</em>: either literal sexual immorality at temple banquets or, metaphorically, spiritual unfaithfulness (syncretism as adultery against God).</p>",
    "15": "<p><strong>homoiōs echeis kai sy tous kratountas tēn didachēn tōn Nikolaitōn</strong>: 'Likewise you also have some who hold the teaching of the Nicolaitans.' <em>Homoiōs</em> (likewise): the Nicolaitan teaching parallels the Balaam-teaching — they are variants of the same accommodation. The church at Pergamum <em>tolerates</em> these teachers; this is the opposite problem from Ephesus, who rightly detected and rejected false apostles (2:2) but lost their first love.</p>",
    "16": "<p><strong>metanoēson oun; ei de mē, erchomai soi tachy kai polemēsō met autōn en tē rhomphaiai tou stomatos mou</strong>: 'Repent therefore; if not, I will come to you quickly and make war against them with the sword of my mouth.' The judgment falls on the false teachers (<em>met autōn</em>, against them), not the whole church — but the church's tolerance of them means Christ's coming-to-judge will affect the community. <em>Erchomai tachy</em>: coming quickly (the same phrase used of the parousia in 3:11; 22:7, 12, 20 — Christ's judicial coming and his final coming use the same language).</p>",
    "17": "<p><strong>tō nikōnti dōsō autō tou manna tou kekrymmenom kai dōsō autō psēphon leukēn kai epi tēn psēphon onoma kainon gegrammenon</strong>: 'To the one who overcomes I will give some of the hidden manna, and a white stone with a new name written on it.' <em>Manna kekrymmenon</em> (hidden manna): Jewish tradition held that Jeremiah hid the golden jar of manna before the exile (2 Macc 2:4-8) for eschatological restoration; the promise reverses the idol-food temptation with true heavenly bread. <em>Psēphos leukē</em> (white stone): possibly an acquittal token (white = innocent in Greek judicial practice), or an invitation tessera for a banquet (social entry token). <em>Onoma kainon</em>: a new name known only to the recipient — personal, intimate identity restored by Christ.</p>",
    "18": "<p><strong>ho huios tou theou, ho echōn tous ophthalmous autou hōs phloga pyros kai hoi podes autou homoioi chalkolibanō</strong>: 'the Son of God, whose eyes are like blazing fire and whose feet are like burnished bronze.' <em>Ho huios tou theou</em> is the only occurrence of this exact title in Revelation — addressing Thyatira, where the imperial cult identified the emperor's son with divine sonship. Christ's sonship displaces the emperor's claim. The fiery eyes (Dan 10:6) signal penetrating omniscience; the bronze feet signal unbreakable authority (the elements from the throne-room vision applied in a context of imminent judgment).</p>",
    "19": "<p><strong>oida sou ta erga kai tēn agapēn kai tēn pistin kai tēn diakonian kai tēn hypomonēn sou</strong>: 'I know your deeds — your love, faith, service, and endurance.' Four virtues in a single catalogue: <em>agapē</em> (love), <em>pistis</em> (faith/faithfulness), <em>diakonia</em> (service/ministry), <em>hypomonē</em> (patient endurance). Thyatira's profile is the strongest of the churches in active virtue. <em>Kai ta eschata pleiōna tōn prōtōn</em>: your recent deeds surpass your earlier ones — the community is growing, not declining.</p>",
    "20": "<p><strong>Ieza bel hē legousa heautēn prophētin</strong>: 'Jezebel, who calls herself a prophetess.' The name Jezebel (<em>Ieza bel</em>) is a pseudonym, alluding to the Phoenician queen of 1 Kgs 16-21 — the historical Jezebel led Ahab into Baal worship and killed the prophets of YHWH. The church at Thyatira tolerates a woman leader who falsely presents herself as a prophetess and promotes exactly the Balaam-pattern of idol-food and sexual immorality. <em>Didaskalei kai plana tous emous doulous</em>: she teaches and misleads my servants — <em>planaō</em> (mislead/deceive) is the word for the wandering of sheep and the deception of false teachers.</p>",
    "21": "<p><strong>kai edōka autē chronon hina metanoēsē, kai ou thelei metanoēsai ek tēs porneias autēs</strong>: 'I gave her time to repent, and she does not want to repent of her sexual immorality.' <em>Edōka chronon</em> (I gave her time): the aorist marks a specific prior opportunity that was not taken. <em>Ou thelei</em> (she does not want/will not): not inability but refusal — the fault is volitional. The seriousness of the judgment that follows (vv. 22-23) is grounded in this refusal after extended opportunity.</p>",
    "22": "<p><strong>ballō autēn eis klinēn kai tous moicheuntas met autēs eis thlipsin megalēn</strong>: 'I will throw her onto a bed of suffering, and those who commit adultery with her into great tribulation.' <em>Klinē</em> (bed): the judgment mirrors the sin — the bed of immorality becomes the bed of illness and suffering. <em>Moicheuntas</em>: committing adultery; both literal (sexual immorality at temple events) and metaphorical (spiritual adultery against God through idolatry). <em>Ean mē metanoēsōsin</em>: unless they repent (aorist subjunctive) — the conditional shows the judgment is not final until the possibility of repentance passes.</p>",
    "23": "<p><strong>ego eimi ho eraunōn nephrous kai kardias</strong>: 'I am the one who searches kidneys and hearts.' <em>Nephrous</em> (kidneys): in Hebrew anthropology, the kidneys are the seat of deep emotion, conscience, and hidden motivation (Jer 17:10; Ps 7:9). The compound <em>nephrous kai kardias</em> (kidneys and hearts) is drawn from the OT divine-judge idiom — the one who searches the hidden depths of human motivation. This is a claim to omniscience about inner dispositions, not just outward behavior.</p>",
    "24": "<p><strong>ta bathē tou satana</strong>: 'the deep things of Satan.' This is evidently the self-description of the false teacher's followers — they boasted of knowing the 'deep things' (possibly a gnosticizing claim to spiritual depth through transgression). The MKT and most modern translations read this as the false teachers' own language, used ironically by Christ. <em>Ou ballō eph hymas allo baros</em>: I will not put any other burden on you — the church members who remain faithful are not required to bear more than holding fast.</p>",
    "25": "<p><strong>plēn ho echete kratēsate achri hou an hēxō</strong>: 'Only hold fast to what you have until I come.' <em>Kratēsate</em> (aorist imperative): seize and hold — a decisive act of grasping. <em>Achri hou an hēxō</em>: until I come — the parousia as the horizon that defines faithful endurance; one holds not forever but until the one who is coming arrives.</p>",
    "26": "<p><strong>kai ho nikōn kai ho tērōn achri telous ta erga mou, dōsō autō exousian epi tōn ethnōn</strong>: 'To the one who overcomes and keeps my works to the end, I will give authority over the nations.' Two present participles (<em>nikōn</em> and <em>tērōn</em>) — overcoming and keeping are ongoing activities, not past accomplishments. <em>Achri telous</em> (to the end): perseverance through the full duration. <em>Exousian epi tōn ethnōn</em>: authority over the nations — sharing in Christ's messianic rule (Ps 2:8-9).</p>",
    "27": "<p><strong>kai poimanei autous en rhabdō sidēra hōs ta skeuē ta keramika syntribetai</strong>: 'He will shepherd them with an iron rod and shatter them like clay vessels.' <em>Poimanei</em> (will shepherd/rule): from <em>poimainō</em>, the shepherd-verb — the iron-rod rule is described with the same word as pastoral care. The LXX of Ps 2:9 uses <em>poimainō</em> for 'rule/break,' preserving the ambiguity of the Hebrew <em>raah</em>. <em>Kathōs kagō eilēpha para tou patros mou</em>: just as I myself have received from my Father — the authority is derived, not autonomous.</p>",
    "28": "<p><strong>dōsō autō ton astera ton prōinon</strong>: 'I will give him the morning star.' The morning star (<em>astēr prōinos</em>) is identified as Christ himself in 22:16 ('I am the root and descendant of David, the bright morning star'). The promise to give the morning star is thus a promise to give Christ himself — the fullest possible eschatological gift. The background may be Num 24:17 ('a star shall come out of Jacob'), the messianic star-prophecy that was applied to the coming ruler in multiple Jewish contexts.</p>",
    "29": "<p><strong>ho echōn ous akousatō ti to pneuma legei tais ekklēsiais</strong>: 'Let anyone who has an ear hear what the Spirit says to the churches.' The closing formula appears in all seven letters. Its movement from singular (addressed to one church) to plural (<em>tais ekklēsiais</em>, the churches) signals that each letter addresses all seven — the community that hears one letter is called to hear all. The Spirit is the one speaking through the glorified Christ: Christology and pneumatology are inseparable in Revelation's vision-structure.</p>"
  },
  "3": {
    "1": "<p><strong>ho echōn ta hepta pneumata tou theou kai tous hepta asteras</strong>: 'the one who holds the seven Spirits of God and the seven stars.' The self-identification shifts from the description in ch. 1 — here the seven Spirits of God (the fullness of the Spirit) are in Christ's possession, linking his authority directly to the Spirit's discernment. <em>Oida sou ta erga, hoti onoma echeis hoti zēis, kai nekros ei</em>: I know your works — you have a reputation for being alive, but you are dead. The contrast is devastating: external reputation (<em>onoma</em>, name/reputation) versus actual spiritual state.</p>",
    "2": "<p><strong>ginou grēgorōn kai stērison ta loipa ha emellon apothanein</strong>: 'Wake up, and strengthen what remains that is about to die.' <em>Ginou grēgorōn</em>: become watchful, a continuous state. <em>Ta loipa</em> (the rest, the remnant): what survives of the community's original vitality. <em>Ou gar heurēka sou ta erga peplērōmena enōpion tou theou mou</em>: I have not found your works complete/full before my God — <em>peplērōmena</em> (perfect passive participle): the works were started but not completed, and the incomplete state persists.</p>",
    "3": "<p><strong>ean oun mē grēgorēsēs, hēxō hōs kleptēs, kai ou mē gnōs poian hōran hēxō epi se</strong>: 'If you will not watch, I will come like a thief, and you will not know at what hour I will come against you.' The thief-coming (<em>hōs kleptēs</em>) is explicitly an unexpected judgment-coming, not the final parousia — Christ comes in historical judgment on unfaithful churches within time. The same <em>hōs kleptēs</em> metaphor appears in Matt 24:43; 1 Thess 5:2; 2 Pet 3:10 for the parousia, but here it is specifically the imminent intra-historical judgment.</p>",
    "4": "<p><strong>alla echeis oliga onomata en Sardesi ha ouk emolynon ta himatia autōn</strong>: 'Yet you have a few names in Sardis who have not soiled their garments.' <em>Onomata</em> (names): individuals; the few faithfully remaining are described by the Hebrew idiom of naming — they are known to God by name. <em>Ouk emolynon ta himatia</em> (did not defile their garments): the metaphor of soiled clothing for moral/spiritual compromise is common in Second Temple literature. <em>Peripathsousin met emou en leukois</em>: they will walk with me in white — the clean garments of the faithful are the eschatological reward.</p>",
    "5": "<p><strong>ho nikōn houtōs peribaleitai en himatios leukois, kai ou mē exaleipsō to onoma autou ek tēs biblou tēs zōēs</strong>: 'The one who overcomes will be clothed in white garments, and I will never blot out his name from the book of life.' The double negative <em>ou mē exaleipsō</em> (I will absolutely never blot out): the strongest negative construction in Greek, providing the most emphatic assurance possible. <em>Exaleipsō</em> (blot out) recalls Moses's intercession (Exod 32:32-33) and Dan 12:1; the promise inverts the threat of erasure with the certainty of permanent inscription.</p>",
    "6": "<p><strong>ho echōn ous akousatō ti to pneuma legei tais ekklēsiais</strong>: Standard closing formula. The repeated formula across all seven letters creates a liturgical rhythm — each letter ends identically, reinforcing that the Spirit's address to one community is for all.</p>",
    "7": "<p><strong>ho hagios, ho alēthinos, ho echōn tēn kleida Dauid, ho anoigōn kai oudeis kleisei, kai kleiōn kai oudeis anoigei</strong>: 'the holy one, the true one, who has the key of David, who opens and no one shuts, who shuts and no one opens.' <em>Hagios</em> and <em>alēthinos</em> (holy and true) are divine attributes applied directly to Christ. The key-of-David language quotes Isa 22:22 (the investiture of Eliakim as royal steward). The two present participles <em>anoigōn</em> and <em>kleiōn</em> in an antithetical pair with <em>oudeis</em> (no one) twice: absolute, unqualified authority over access to the divine household.</p>",
    "8": "<p><strong>idou dedōka enōpion sou thyran ēnoigmenēn, hēn oudeis dynatai kleisai autēn</strong>: 'Behold, I have placed before you an open door that no one is able to shut.' <em>Dedōka</em> (perfect): I have given and it stands given — the open door is an accomplished and ongoing reality. <em>Ēnoigmenēn</em> (perfect passive participle): the door has been opened and remains open. <em>Dynamin mikran</em> (little power/strength): Philadelphia is weak by worldly measures; the open door is given to the weak church, not the strong one.</p>",
    "9": "<p><strong>idou didō ek tēs synagōgēs tou satana tōn legontōn heautous Ioudaious einai kai ouk eisin alla pseudontai</strong>: 'Behold, I will make those of the synagogue of Satan who say they are Jews and are not, but lie.' The future <em>poiēsō autous hina hēxousin kai proskyneousin enōpion tōn podōn sou</em> (I will make them come and bow down at your feet): this is an inversion of the Isaianic promises where nations bow before restored Israel (Isa 49:23; 60:14); the persecutors will acknowledge the vindication of the oppressed community. <em>Kagō ēgapēsa se</em>: that I have loved you (aorist) — the vindication proves the prior love.</p>",
    "10": "<p><strong>hoti etērēsas ton logon tēs hypomonēs mou, kagō se tērēsō ek tēs hōras tou peirasmou</strong>: 'Because you have kept the word of my patient endurance, I will also keep you from the hour of trial.' The symmetry of keeping: the community kept Christ's word; Christ keeps the community. <em>Tēs horas tou peirasmou</em> (the hour of trial): possibly a specific future tribulation period or more generally the eschatological pressure. <em>Ek tēs hōras</em> (from the hour): the preposition <em>ek</em> (out from) is debated — does it mean preservation through the trial or removal before it begins?</p>",
    "11": "<p><strong>erchomai tachy; kratei ho echeis, hina mēdeis labē ton stephanon sou</strong>: 'I am coming quickly. Hold fast what you have, so that no one may seize your crown.' <em>Erchomai tachy</em>: present-tense coming, imminent arrival. <em>Kratei</em> (aorist imperative): seize/hold firm — decisive act of retention. <em>Ton stephanon sou</em>: your crown — the <em>stephanos</em> (victor's wreath) can be seized by another if you do not persevere; crowns in Revelation are conditionally held.</p>",
    "12": "<p><strong>ho nikōn, poiēsō auton stylon en tō naō tou theou mou</strong>: 'The one who overcomes, I will make him a pillar in the temple of my God.' <em>Stylon</em> (pillar): structural element, immovable, permanent — contrasts with Philadelphia's earthquake vulnerability (major earthquakes struck the region ca. 17 CE; pillars that stood were the prize of survivors). <em>Exō ouk exeleusetai eti</em>: he will go out no more — the conqueror's place in the divine temple is permanent, unlike a city that might be evacuated for safety. The threefold writing on the pillar (name of God, name of the city, Christ's new name) inscribes triple identity on the victor.</p>",
    "13": "<p>Standard closing formula; see 2:7.</p>",
    "14": "<p><strong>ho Amēn, ho martys ho pistos kai alēthinos, hē archē tēs ktiseōs tou theou</strong>: 'the Amen, the faithful and true witness, the beginning of God's creation.' <em>Ho Amēn</em> as a title: drawn from Isa 65:16 (<em>elohei amen</em>, God of the Amen/God of truth). <em>Archē tēs ktiseōs</em> (the beginning of creation): this is the most debated phrase in the seven letters. <em>Archē</em> can mean first-in-time (as Arians argued: the first created being) or source/ruler (as orthodox interpreters argued, citing Col 1:15-18's firstborn-of-creation language meaning sovereign over creation). The context — presenting Christ as the one who holds the Seven Spirits and seven stars, who is divine witness and divine Amen — supports the ruler/source reading.</p>",
    "15": "<p><strong>oida sou ta erga, hoti oute psychros ei oute zestos; ophelon psychros ēs ē zestos</strong>: 'I know your works: you are neither cold nor hot; would that you were cold or hot.' The commercial metaphor uses temperature to describe spiritual vitality. Cold water (from Colossae) and hot water (from Hierapolis) both had uses; Laodicea's lukewarm water supply (from mineral springs) was medically unpleasant. The lukewarm church has no distinctiveness — neither refreshing nor curative, merely tepid.</p>",
    "16": "<p><strong>houtōs, hoti chlioros ei kai oute zestos oute psychros, mellō se emesai ek tou stomatos mou</strong>: 'So, because you are lukewarm, and neither hot nor cold, I will spit you out of my mouth.' <em>Emesai</em> (vomit out): strong visceral imagery — the reaction of a body to something that causes nausea. <em>Mellō</em> (I am about to): the expulsion is imminent, not yet enacted — the conditional structure of vv. 19-20 implies repentance can avert it. The severity of the language to the wealthiest of the seven churches is deliberate.</p>",
    "17": "<p><strong>hoti legeis hoti plousios eimi kai peploutēka kai ouden chreian echō</strong>: 'Because you say, I am rich and I have prospered and I need nothing.' <em>Plousios</em> (rich) and <em>peploutēka</em> (I have grown rich, perfect) — Laodicea was one of the wealthiest cities in Asia, known for banking, textile manufacture, and medicine. The perfect tense <em>peploutēka</em> expresses the settled self-confidence of accumulated wealth. The five-fold description of their actual state — wretched, pitiable, poor, blind, naked — inverts the five-fold prosperity they claim.</p>",
    "18": "<p><strong>symbouleuō soi agorasai par emou chrysion pepyrōmenon ek pyros hina ploutēsēs</strong>: 'I counsel you to buy from me gold refined by fire, so that you may be rich.' The commercial metaphor uses marketplace language against Laodicea's commercial pride — they are to buy from Christ. <em>Chrysion pepyrōmenon ek pyros</em> (gold refined/purified by fire): true spiritual wealth earned through testing. <em>Kollyrion</em> (eye salve): Laodicea was famous for <em>Phrygian powder</em> used as a medical eye treatment; the city's pharmacological reputation becomes the ironic vehicle for Christ's offer of genuine spiritual sight.</p>",
    "19": "<p><strong>egō hosous ean philō elegchō kai paideuō; zēleue oun kai metanoēson</strong>: 'Those whom I love, I rebuke and discipline. So be zealous and repent.' <em>Elegchō</em> (rebuke/convict) and <em>paideuō</em> (discipline/train): both terms carry the flavor of parental correction (Prov 3:12; Heb 12:6). The severity of the Laodicea letter is thus reframed as love's most direct form. <em>Zēleue</em> (aorist imperative): be zealous, be fired up — the antidote to lukewarmness is not moderation but ignition.</p>",
    "20": "<p><strong>idou hestēka epi tēn thyran kai krouō; ean tis akousē tēs phōnēs mou kai anoixē tēn thyran, eiseleusomai pros auton kai deipnēsō met autou kai autos met emou</strong>: 'Behold, I have been standing at the door and knocking; if anyone hears my voice and opens the door, I will come in and eat with him, and he with me.' <em>Hestēka</em> (perfect): I have been standing and stand — ongoing presence, not a momentary visit. <em>Krouō</em> (present): continuous knocking. The <em>deipnon</em> (evening meal, the main meal of the day) implies covenant fellowship — shared table in antiquity was the most intimate expression of relationship and commitment. Notably this promise is to individuals within the church (<em>tis</em>, anyone), not the community as a whole; Laodicea is so far gone that Christ knocks for any individual willing to open.</p>",
    "21": "<p><strong>ho nikōn, dōsō autō kathisai met emou en tō thronō mou, hōs kagō enikekon kai ekathisa meta tou patros mou en tō thronō autou</strong>: 'The one who overcomes, I will grant him to sit with me on my throne, as I also overcame and sat down with my Father on his throne.' The highest promise in the seven letters: sharing Christ's throne. <em>Enikekon</em> (perfect): I have conquered and remain in the state of having conquered — the perfect here captures the ongoing ruling status of the risen Christ at the Father's right hand (Ps 110:1; Heb 1:3). The conqueror participates in what Christ has already accomplished: the promise extends Christ's own victory-throne to the faithful community.</p>",
    "22": "<p>Standard closing formula; see 2:7.</p>"
  },
  "4": {
    "1": "<p><strong>idou thyra ēnoigmenē en tō ouranō</strong>: 'Behold, a door was standing open in heaven.' <em>Ēnoigmenē</em> (perfect passive participle): the door had been opened and stands open — not freshly opened at the moment of John's vision but already-open for his entry. <em>Anaba hōde kai deixō soi ha dei genesthai meta tauta</em>: come up here and I will show you what must take place after these things — <em>dei genesthai</em> (must happen) repeats the divine necessity of 1:1. The ascent structure follows Jewish apocalyptic convention (1 Enoch, 2 Enoch, Isa 6) — the seer is taken up to receive the heavenly perspective on earthly events.</p>",
    "2": "<p><strong>euthēōs egenomēn en pneumati</strong>: 'immediately I was in the Spirit.' The second Spirit-transport in Revelation (cf. 1:10) — <em>egenomēn en pneumati</em> (aorist: I came to be in the Spirit) marks a definite transition. <em>Kai idou thronos ekeito en tō ouranō, kai epi ton thronon kathēmenos</strong>: the throne as the visual center of the vision — who sits on it is not immediately named but described in terms of precious-stone appearance, deliberately avoiding direct description of the divine form (as in Ezek 1:26-28, which speaks of 'something like' human form on the throne).</p>",
    "3": "<p><strong>ho kathēmenos homoios horasei lithō iaspidi kai sardios, kai iris kyklothen tou thronou homoios horasei smaragdinō</strong>: 'the one seated had the appearance of jasper and carnelian, and around the throne was a rainbow that had the appearance of an emerald.' The description proceeds entirely through simile (<em>homoios</em>: like, resembling) — the divine form is never described directly, only through layers of comparison. <em>Iaspis</em> (jasper): translucent crystal (21:11 calls it 'clear as crystal'); <em>sardios</em> (carnelian): deep red. The rainbow (<em>iris</em>) of emerald green alludes to Ezek 1:28 (the rainbow around the divine glory) — God's covenant promise encircling his throne.</p>",
    "4": "<p><strong>kyklothen tou thronou thronoi eikosi tessares, kai epi tous thronous eikosi tessaras presbyterous kathēmenous</strong>: 'Around the throne were twenty-four thrones, and seated on the thrones were twenty-four elders.' <em>Eikosi tessaras presbyterous</em>: the identity of the twenty-four elders is debated. Three main proposals: (1) the 24 Davidic priestly courses of 1 Chr 24:1-19; (2) the 12 patriarchs + 12 apostles (the whole covenant people); (3) an angelic council. Their white garments and golden <em>stephanoi</em> (victor's wreaths, not royal crowns) favor a redeemed-humanity reading. The position of sitting on thrones signals delegated authority.</p>",
    "5": "<p><strong>kai ek tou thronou ekporeuontai astrapai kai phōnai kai brontai</strong>: 'From the throne come flashes of lightning and rumblings and peals of thunder.' The three-element theophany formula (lightning, voices, thunder) recurs at each major structural marker in Revelation (8:5; 11:19; 16:18), always with escalating intensity — this is the Sinai-theophany pattern (Exod 19:16) transposed to the heavenly throne. <em>Hepta lampades pyros kaiomenai enōpion tou thronou, hai eisin ta hepta pneumata tou theou</em>: the seven torches are identified as the seven Spirits of God — the same Spirit-fullness present in the churches (1:4; 3:1) is here a blazing heavenly presence before the throne.</p>",
    "6": "<p><strong>kai enōpion tou thronou hōs thalassa hyalinē homoion krystallō</strong>: 'Before the throne was something like a sea of glass, like crystal.' The glassy sea combines the bronze sea of Solomon's temple (1 Kgs 7:23-26, the large basin for priestly purification) and the sapphire pavement of Exod 24:10 (where the elders saw God at Sinai). <em>Tessara zōia gemonta ophthalmon emprosthen kai opisthen</em>: four living creatures full of eyes in front and behind — omniscient, all-seeing, combining Ezekiel's four creatures (Ezek 1:5-14) with Isaiah's seraphim (Isa 6:2-3).</p>",
    "7": "<p><strong>to zōon to prōton homoion leonti, kai to deuteron zōon homoion moschō, kai to triton zōon echon to prosōpon hōs anthrōpou, kai to tetarton zōon homoion aetō petomenō</strong>: the four faces — lion, ox (or calf: <em>moschos</em>), human, eagle — correspond to Ezek 1:10's four faces of the heavenly creatures. In patristic tradition these four were linked to the four Evangelists (Irenaeus; Jerome). More precisely, they represent the four royal/divine qualities: lion (king of beasts, power), ox (service, sacrifice), human (intelligence, reason), eagle (divinity, transcendence, heaven).</p>",
    "9": "<p><strong>kai hotan dōsousin ta zōia doxan kai timēn kai eucharistian tō kathēmenō epi tō thronō</strong>: 'And whenever the living creatures give glory and honor and thanksgiving to him who is seated on the throne.' The temporal conjunction <em>hotan</em> (whenever) + future indicatives describes an ongoing, repeated liturgical cycle — the heavenly worship is continual. The three-fold <em>doxa, timē, eucharistia</em> (glory, honor, thanksgiving) forms a liturgical pattern that the twenty-four elders' response (v. 10) expands.</p>",
    "10": "<p><strong>pesountai hoi eikosi tessares presbyteroi enōpion tou kathēmenou epi tou thronou kai proskyneusousin tō zōnti eis tous aiōnas tōn aiōnōn kai balousin tous stephanous autōn enōpion tou thronou</strong>: 'The twenty-four elders will fall down before him who is seated on the throne and worship him who lives forever and ever, and they cast their crowns before the throne.' The casting of <em>stephanoi</em> (crowns/wreaths) before the throne is the decisive gesture: the elders' authority and victory belongs to God, not to themselves. The victor's wreath has no meaning except as returned to its source.</p>",
    "11": "<p><strong>axios ei, ho kyrios kai ho theos hēmōn, labein tēn doxan kai tēn timēn kai tēn dynamin</strong>: 'Worthy are you, our Lord and God, to receive glory and honor and power.' <em>Axios</em> (worthy) is the key term of chs. 4-5: first applied to God in the creation-doxology, then contested in ch. 5 (who is worthy to open the scroll?), then applied to the Lamb (5:9, 12). <em>Ho kyrios kai ho theos hēmōn</em>: 'our Lord and God' — this is precisely the title that the Emperor Domitian demanded for himself (<em>Dominus et Deus noster</em>); the throne-room doxology directly counters the imperial claim.</p>"
  },
  "5": {
    "1": "<p><strong>kai eidon epi tēn dexian tou kathēmenou epi tou thronou biblion gegrammenon esōthen kai opisthen, katesphraismenon sphragisin hepta</strong>: 'I saw in the right hand of him seated on the throne a scroll written inside and on the back, sealed with seven seals.' <em>Esōthen kai opisthen</em> (inside and on the back): an <em>opisthographon</em> — a scroll written on both sides. Such scrolls were rare and indicated a document so full in content it overflowed the standard single-side. Seven seals: divine completeness/perfection of the sealing — the scroll's contents are fully secured and cannot be accessed until the seals are broken by the worthy one.</p>",
    "2": "<p><strong>kai eidon aggelon ischyron kēryssonta en phōnē megalē; Tis axios anoixai to biblion kai lysai tas sphragas autou</strong>: 'I saw a mighty angel proclaiming with a loud voice: Who is worthy to open the scroll and break its seals?' <em>Ischuron aggelon</em> (mighty angel): this figure appears again in 10:1 and 18:21 — a supernaturally powerful heavenly being whose proclamation traverses the entire cosmos (v. 3). <em>Axios</em> (worthy): the scroll-crisis is a worthiness test; no one passes initially, intensifying the revelation of the Lamb's singular qualification.</p>",
    "3": "<p><strong>kai oudeis edynato en tō ouranō oude epi tēs gēs oude hypokatō tēs gēs anoixai to biblion oude blepein auto</strong>: 'No one in heaven or on earth or under the earth was able to open the scroll or to look into it.' The tripartite cosmos (heaven, earth, underworld) is searched exhaustively — no created being anywhere in existence meets the criterion. The totality of the failure intensifies the worthiness of the one who does step forward.</p>",
    "4": "<p><strong>kai eklaion poly, hoti oudeis axios heurethē anoixai to biblion oude blepein auto</strong>: 'I wept greatly because no one was found worthy to open the scroll or to look into it.' <em>Eklaion</em> (imperfect): ongoing weeping, not a single cry. The imperfect captures John's sustained distress while the search proved fruitless. The scroll contains the plan of God for history (chs. 6-22 unfold its contents) — if no one can open it, history has no redemptive resolution. John weeps for the apparent inaccessibility of God's purpose.</p>",
    "5": "<p><strong>enikesen ho leōn ho ek tēs phylēs Iouda, hē riza Dauid anoixai to biblion kai tas hepta sphragas autou</strong>: 'The Lion of the tribe of Judah, the Root of David, has conquered, so that he can open the scroll and its seven seals.' The title-cluster is Christological recapitulation: <em>Leon ek phyles Iouda</em> (Lion-of-Judah: Gen 49:9-10), <em>Riza David</em> (Root of David: Isa 11:1, 10; Rev 22:16), <em>enikesen</em> (has conquered). Then the stunning inversion: the 'Lion' who conquers is revealed as a 'Lamb standing as if slain' (v. 6). John hears Lion, then sees Lamb — the conquering is through the cross, not through military force. This Lion-Lamb inversion is Revelation's central hermeneutic: power is redefined by the slain Lamb who stands.</p>",
    "6": "<p><strong>arnion hestēkos hōs esphagmenon, echon kerata hepta kai ophthalmous hepta</strong>: 'a Lamb standing, as though it had been slain, with seven horns and seven eyes.' <em>Arnion</em> (little lamb): Revelation's preferred word for Christ (29 times), distinct from <em>amnos</em> (used in John 1:29; 1 Pet 1:19). The diminutive <em>arnion</em> emphasizes smallness and vulnerability. <em>Hōs esphagmenon</em> (as if slain): the wounds of the cross are visible in the glorified body — the Lamb bears permanent marks of sacrifice. <em>Hestēkos</em> (standing, perfect participle): it was slain but stands — resurrection expressed in a participle. Seven horns (omnipotence, via the OT horn-as-power symbol) + seven eyes (omniscience, identified as the seven Spirits of God) = the slain Lamb who is simultaneously omnipotent and omniscient.</p>",
    "7": "<p><strong>kai ēlthen kai eilēphen ek tēs dexias tou kathēmenou epi tou thronou</strong>: 'He came and took it from the right hand of him seated on the throne.' Two aorists in sequence: <em>ēlthen</em> (came) and <em>eilēphen</em> (took). The taking is a decisive act — the Lamb approaches and receives the scroll from God's hand. In the context of the worthiness contest (vv. 2-4), this single action resolves the cosmic crisis: the one worthy to open history's scroll is the slain Lamb, and he takes what belongs to him.</p>",
    "8": "<p><strong>phialas chrysas gemousas thymiamaton, hai eisin hai proseuchai tōn hagiōn</strong>: 'golden bowls full of incense, which are the prayers of the saints.' The identification is explicit: the incense in the heavenly temple is the accumulated prayers of the community on earth. In the OT, incense was offered on the golden altar before the Most Holy Place (Exod 30:1-10) as a symbol of prayers ascending to God. Here the twenty-four elders and four living creatures hold the very prayers of the church — every prayer uttered on earth has a heavenly counterpart in these bowls. <em>Kitharan</em> (harp): liturgical instrument, the instrument of Levitical temple worship (1 Chr 25:1-8).</p>",
    "9": "<p><strong>ōdēn kainēn</strong>: 'a new song.' The <em>ōdē kainē</em> formula (Ps 96:1; 98:1; 144:9; Isa 42:10) marks the song as celebrating a new redemptive act of God — not repetition of a known melody but improvised praise for an unprecedented deed. <em>Hoti esphagēs kai ēgorasas tō haimati sou</strong> (because you were slain and purchased with your blood): the ground of the new song is the cross. <em>Ēgorasas</em> (you purchased): the aorist of <em>agorazō</em> (to buy in the marketplace) — redemption as purchase, the language of manumission. The price was Christ's blood.</p>",
    "10": "<p><strong>kai epoiēsas autous tō theō hēmōn basileian kai hiereis kai basileusousin epi tēs gēs</strong>: 'You made them a kingdom and priests to our God, and they shall reign on the earth.' The repetition of Exod 19:6 (cf. 1:6) now placed in the mouth of the heavenly choir as a completed fact: the cross has constituted the redeemed community as kingdom-priests. <em>Basileusousin epi tēs gēs</em> (they shall reign on the earth): future tense — the eschatological reign has not yet arrived but is secured; the kingdom is real and its earthly expression is coming.</p>",
    "11": "<p><strong>kai ēkousa phōnēn aggelōn pollōn kyklothen tou thronou kai tōn zōōn kai tōn presbyterōn, kai ēn ho arithmos autōn myriades myriadōn kai chiliades chiliadōn</strong>: 'I heard around the throne the voice of many angels, and their number was myriads of myriads and thousands of thousands.' <em>Myriades myriadōn kai chiliades chiliadōn</em>: drawn from Dan 7:10's description of the heavenly court (ten thousand times ten thousand stood before him). The number is maximally indefinite — uncountable multitudes. The witness expands from the four living creatures and twenty-four elders (v. 8) to the full angelic choir.</p>",
    "12": "<p><strong>axios estin to arnion to esphagmenon labein tēn dynamin kai plouton kai sophian kai ischyn kai timēn kai doxan kai eulogian</strong>: 'Worthy is the Lamb who was slain, to receive power and wealth and wisdom and might and honor and glory and blessing.' Seven attributes in the doxology (seven = completeness): <em>dynamis, ploutos, sophia, ischus, timē, doxa, eulogia</em>. This sevenfold doxology to the Lamb matches the threefold doxology to God in v. 11 and the fourfold in v. 13 — the deliberate numerical escalation reaching seven for the Lamb signals the fullness of divine honor directed to Christ. <em>Ho esphagmenon</em> (the slain one): the perfect participle — the slaying is a permanent defining characteristic of the Lamb's identity even in glory.</p>",
    "13": "<p><strong>pasan ktistin hē en tō ouranō kai epi tēs gēs kai hypokatō tēs gēs kai epi tēs thalassēs kai ta en autois</strong>: 'Every creature in heaven and on earth and under the earth and in the sea and all that is in them.' The fourfold enumeration surpasses even the triple-cosmos of v. 3 — the sea is added as a fourth domain. The scope is absolute: no creature is excluded from the worship that concludes ch. 5. The doxology to 'him who sits on the throne and to the Lamb' places the Lamb as co-recipient of cosmic worship with God.</p>",
    "14": "<p><strong>kai ta tessara zōia elegon Amēn</strong>: 'And the four living creatures said Amen.' <em>Amēn</em> as the liturgical seal of the cosmic doxology: the four living creatures who represent all creation affirm what every creature has sung. <em>Kai hoi presbyteroi epesan kai prosekynesan</em>: and the elders fell down and worshiped — the same prostration as in v. 8, now as the conclusion of the entire throne-room scene. The chapter ends in worship; Revelation's entire eschatological vision is framed by and resolved into worship of the Lamb.</p>"
  },
  "13": {
    "18": "<p><strong>de estin sophia ho echon noun psephisato ton arithmon tou theriou arithmos gar anthropou estin kai ho arithmos autou hexakosioi hexekonta hex</strong>: '666' — the number of the beast. <em>Arithmos anthropou</em> (number of a human/humanity) — the beast's number is not cosmic but human, not transcendent but sub-divine. <em>Gematria</em> (assigning numerical values to letters) was a common Greco-Roman literary technique. The best-attested solution: NERON KAISER in Hebrew letters (nun=50 + resh=200 + vav=6 + nun=50 + qoph=100 + samek=60 + resh=200 = 666). Nero Caesar as the prototype of the beast — the first Roman persecutor of Christians — makes the political-historical reference legible to John's seven churches (ca. 90-95 CE, under Domitian, the 'second Nero').</p>"
  },
  "21": {
    "3": "<p><strong>idou he skene tou theou meta ton anthropon kai skemnosei met auton</strong>: 'Behold the dwelling place (<em>skene</em>) of God is with people, and he will dwell (<em>skenosei</em>) with them.' The <em>skene</em>-language deliberately echoes the wilderness tabernacle (<em>Mishkan</em>) and anticipates John 1:14 where the Word <em>eskenosen</em> (tabernacled) among us. The eschatological new creation is the realization of what the tabernacle mediated: direct divine presence without the veil, without the intermediary system, without separation — YHWH's face-to-face dwelling with his people. The Sinai covenant promise reaches its telos in the new Jerusalem.</p>"
  },
  "22": {
    "20": "<p><strong>nai erchomai tachy</strong> (<em>nai erchomai tachy</em>): 'Surely I am coming soon.' The final direct speech of Christ in the canon is a promise of return. <em>Tachy</em> (soon/quickly): the eschatological urgency that has characterized the entire Revelation. The community's response — <em>Amen, erchou Kyrie Iesou</em> (Come, Lord Jesus) — is the Greek form of the Aramaic <em>Maranatha</em> (1 Cor 16:22; Didache 10:6). The canon ends with a promise and a prayer: Christ's 'I am coming' and the community's 'Come.' The entire Christian life is lived in this tension of promise-and-prayer, the <em>already</em> of Christ's victory and the <em>not yet</em> of his return.</p>"
  }
}

REV_CONTEXT = {
  "1": {
    "9": "<p>The island of Patmos is a small volcanic island in the Aegean Sea, part of the Dodecanese chain, about 37 miles southwest of Ephesus. The Roman practice of <em>relegatio in insulam</em> (banishment to an island) was used for political offenders of some status — those meriting death were executed, those of social standing were exiled. John's Patmos exile 'on account of the word of God and the testimony of Jesus' (v. 9) places the Revelation within the Roman persecution of Christians, most plausibly under Domitian (81-96 CE, who demanded to be addressed as <em>Dominus et Deus</em>, Lord and God — a title the Revelation's 'Lord God Almighty' directly counters). The imperial cult was particularly strong in the seven cities of Revelation (Smyrna, Pergamum, Thyatira, Sardis, Philadelphia, Laodicea, and Ephesus all had imperial temples and cult practices).</p>"
  },
  "4": {
    "1": "<p>John's heavenly ascent follows the well-established pattern of Jewish apocalyptic merkabah mysticism (throne-chariot speculation based on Ezek 1 and Isa 6). The rabbinic tradition (b. Hagigah 11b-16a) treated merkabah speculation as dangerous esoterica — only the wisest scholars should study it. John's vision democratizes the throne-room: every Christian is shown what the mystical traditions reserved for elite initiates. The four living creatures (combining Ezek 1:5-14's four creatures with Isa 6:2-3's seraphim) and the twenty-four elders (representing either the twelve patriarchs + twelve apostles, or the twenty-four priestly courses of 1 Chr 24) frame the throne in the same pattern as the OT heavenly-temple tradition.</p>"
  },
  "12": {
    "1": "<p>The woman clothed with the sun (ch. 12) has generated three major interpretive traditions: (1) the church giving birth to Christ and then fleeing persecution (corporate-ecclesial reading); (2) Mary (Roman Catholic tradition, citing Gen 3:15 and the Immaculate Conception typology); (3) Israel/the covenant community through whom the Messiah came (salvation-historical reading). The best reading combines 2 and 3: the woman is the covenant community (OT Israel → NT church) through whom the Messiah came; Mary is the proximate historical instantiation. The cosmic imagery (sun, moon, twelve stars = Gen 37:9's dream of Joseph) links the woman to the patriarchal promise-community.</p>"
  },
  "17": {
    "9": "<p>The seven hills on which the woman sits (v. 9: <em>hepta ore</em>) is the most explicit historical identification in Revelation — Rome was universally known as the 'city of seven hills' (Septemontium). The woman 'Babylon the great' (vv. 5, 18: 'the great city that has dominion over the kings of the earth') is Rome — coded in the 'Babylon' cipher that 1 Peter also uses (1 Pet 5:13). Jewish and Christian apocalyptic literature routinely used 'Babylon' for Rome as the current oppressive empire (4 Ezra 3:1-2, 28-31; 2 Baruch 10-11). The coding protected the text from Roman censorship while being transparent to readers in the seven churches who knew the 'mystery' (v. 7).</p>"
  }
}

REV_CHRIST = {
  "1": {
    "17": "<p>A direct revelation: 'I am the first and the last, and the living one. I died, and behold I am alive forevermore, and I have the keys of Death and Hades.' Three layered claims: (1) divine identity — the first-and-last YHWH-title; (2) resurrection reality — I died and I live; (3) eschatological authority — I hold the keys to death and Hades. These three together constitute the Christological thesis of Revelation: the crucified and risen Lord is the sovereign YHWH who controls death itself. The entire apocalyptic vision — judgments, seals, trumpets, bowls, the final victory — flows from this threefold claim made by Christ to John on Patmos.</p>"
  },
  "5": {
    "6": "<p>A direct revelation: 'A Lamb standing, as though it had been slain, with seven horns and seven eyes, which are the seven spirits of God sent out into all the earth.' The Lamb-vision is Revelation's Christological center. The Lamb is: (1) slain — bearing the marks of the cross permanently in his resurrection body; (2) standing — the resurrection state; (3) with seven horns — omnipotent (seven = completeness; horns = power); (4) with seven eyes — omniscient. This is the highest Christological symbol in the canon: the crucified-and-risen Jesus is simultaneously the sacrificial victim and the omnipotent, omniscient Lord of all history. The entire drama of Revelation unfolds as this Lamb opens the seals of history.</p>",

    "12": "<p>A direct revelation: 'Worthy is the Lamb who was slain, to receive power and wealth and wisdom and might and honor and glory and blessing!' The sevenfold doxology directed to the Lamb matches the sevenfold doxology directed to God in v. 13 — the deliberate parallelism attributes to Christ the same divine worthiness that belongs to YHWH alone. The ground of worthiness is the slaying (<em>ho esphagmenos</em>) — the cross is the qualification for cosmic lordship. The order in the throne-room is anti-imperial: not the emperor who receives tribute but the crucified-and-exalted Lamb who receives worship from every creature.</p>"
  },
  "19": {
    "16": "<p>A direct revelation: 'On his robe and on his thigh he has a name written: King of kings and Lord of lords.' The rider on the white horse — identified in vv. 11-16 with 'Faithful and True,' with eyes like flame, with many diadems, clothed in blood-stained robe, wielding a sharp sword from his mouth — bears the supreme title that Deut 10:17 gives to YHWH (God of gods and Lord of lords). Jesus as King-of-kings and Lord-of-lords is the final Christological counter-claim to every imperial title: Caesar's claim to divine lordship is answered by the appearance of the one whose sovereignty is not shared and whose kingdom will not be destroyed.</p>"
  },
  "21": {
    "5": "<p>A direct revelation: 'And he who was seated on the throne said: Behold, I am making all things new.' In the new creation vision, the one seated on the throne (identified with the Lamb in 22:1, 3 where both are said to be the throne of the new Jerusalem) speaks the new creation into being. The <em>kaina</em> (new, qualitatively new) of v. 5 echoes 2 Cor 5:17 (new creation) and Isa 65:17 — the eschatological renewal is not the old patched up but the new inaugurated by divine decree. The Christological new creation: as Christ's word created the old order (John 1:3; Col 1:16), so his word re-creates the new.</p>"
  },
  "22": {
    "13": "<p>A direct revelation: 'I am the Alpha and the Omega, the first and the last, the beginning and the end.' Revelation's closing divine address: Jesus claims for himself the three divine-identity formulae that the book opened with in relation to the Father (1:8: Alpha-Omega + Almighty). The three phrases together (Alpha/Omega, first/last, beginning/end) constitute the most comprehensive divine self-identification in the canon — and the book assigns them to Jesus. The Christological conclusion of Revelation: the Jesus who was crucified under Pontius Pilate, who was raised and ascended, who will return, is the one to whom all time and all reality belong. He is the beginning and the end of all creation.</p>"
  }
}

def main():
    e = load_echo('revelation')
    merge_echo(e, REV_ECHO)
    save_echo('revelation', e)
    print(f'Rev echo: {len(e)} chapters, {sum(len(v) for v in e.values())} verses')

    c = load_comm('mkt-original', 'revelation')
    merge_comm(c, REV_ORIGINAL)
    save_comm('mkt-original', 'revelation', c)
    print(f'Rev original: {len(c)} chapters, {sum(len(v) for v in c.values())} verses')

    c = load_comm('mkt-context', 'revelation')
    merge_comm(c, REV_CONTEXT)
    save_comm('mkt-context', 'revelation', c)
    print(f'Rev context: {len(c)} chapters, {sum(len(v) for v in c.values())} verses')

    c = load_comm('mkt-christ', 'revelation')
    merge_comm(c, REV_CHRIST)
    save_comm('mkt-christ', 'revelation', c)
    print(f'Rev christ: {len(c)} chapters, {sum(len(v) for v in c.values())} verses')

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
